        "conclusion": "Patient demonstrates significant force asymmetry (SI=32.1%) with the left foot bearing substantially more load (avg 361N) compared to the right (avg 261N), consistent with right-leg protective weight bearing. Cadence is within normal range at 116 steps/min with very low stride-to-stride variability (CV<0.01), suggesting a compensated but stable gait pattern.",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><h3>Smart Insole Gait Analysis Report</h3>\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong> Patient demonstrates significant force asymmetry (SI=32.1%) with the left foot bearing substantially more load (avg 361N) compared to the right (avg 261N), consistent with right-leg protective weight bearing. Cadence is within normal range at 116 steps/min with very low stride-to-stride variability (CV<0.01), suggesting a compensated but stable gait pattern.</p>\n<p><strong>Weight Bearing:</strong> partial \u2014 Right foot peak force ~261N represents ~32% body weight (82kg). If toe-touch WB prescribed (max 20% BW = 160N), patient is exceeding the restriction by approximately 60%.</p>\n<p><strong>Symmetry:</strong> moderately_asymmetric \u2014 Pattern consistent with antalgic gait \u2014 patient maintains normal stride timing but offloads the surgical limb. The force differential suggests either pain-mediated guarding or insufficient confidence in the repair.</p>\n<p><strong>Gait Quality:</strong> Cadence normal, Variability normal</p>\n<p><strong>Risk Flags:</strong></p><ul>\n<li>Weight bearing exceeds prescribed toe-touch limit on right foot</li>\n<li>Force asymmetry >30% \u2014 risk of contralateral overloading injuries (hip, knee, lower back)</li>\n<li>Left stance phase prolonged (79.7% vs 74.6%) indicating compensatory loading</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Recommendations:</strong></p><ul>\n<li>Review weight-bearing restriction compliance \u2014 patient exceeding 20% BW limit</li>\n<li>Assess for pain at surgical site that may be driving protective unloading</li>\n<li>Monitor left hip and knee for early signs of compensatory overload</li>\n<li>Consider active feedback insole alerts when right foot exceeds 160N threshold</li>\n<li>Schedule follow-up gait assessment in 5-7 days to track progression</li>\n</ul></div>"
